##
# How to Edit Taxonomy in Arctos

## Users with taxonomic authority can edit taxonomy by altering an individual taxonomic record or by using the Hierarchical tool to manage multiple records.  These instructions cover the editing of individual records.  See [How to Manage Taxonomy hierarchically](http://handbook.arctosdb.org/how_to/How-to-Manage-Taxonomy-Hierarchically.html) to manage multiple taxa.

###
## Taxon Names

Taxon Names cannot be edited.  They can be deleted (see below).  Do not consciously create names of no value, misspelled names, etc. and use the link [Comment or report bad data] on the taxon page if you find one.

##
## Validation Service

Arctos checks taxon names against various services when they are created or edited. This check is a tool, not an authority; all services have significant problems as of this writing. &quot;Valid&quot; names will occasionally be flagged as invalid, and erroneous names will occasionally pass.  One of the services contains data from Arctos, so the check is a bit circular. Users remain fully responsible for the content of Arctos taxonomy. &quot;Valid for Arctos&quot; taxonomy is described in[Taxonomy](http://handbook.arctosdb.org/documentation/taxonomy.html)in Documentation.

###
## To edit an existing record

###
## Editing Non-Classification data

### Open the record that you need to edit.  In this case, we need to make a change of the taxon status from valid to invalid.  The authority for this change is the World Register of Marine Species.

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

### We open the record for _Haliotis mariae dentata_.

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

### Click [Edit Classification] which links to a screen with the classification and non-classification terms.

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

### We want to change the non-classification data.  We change the taxon status from &quot;valid&quot; to &quot;invalid.&quot;  We add the source of the change to the &quot;source\_authority&quot; field.  Alternatively, this could be placed in a &quot;remark&quot; field.

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

### After making the changes, click &quot;Save Edits&quot; then [View Taxon Page] to see the edits as they will appear on the taxon page.

###
## Editing Taxon Relationship

### Since we have changed the taxon status to &quot;invalid,&quot; we need to link to the valid taxon.  In this case, WoRMS shows the valid taxon to be _Haliotis mariae_.  This is additional Non-Classification Data that is entered on a separate screen.

### In this case, we want to create _Haliotis mariae_ as the &quot;accepted synonym&quot; (some prefer &quot;senior synonym&quot;) of _Haliotis mariae dentata&quot;_ or, in the reverse _Haliotis mariae dentata_ as the &quot;junior synonym&quot; of _Haliotis mariae.  _This can be done from either taxon page.  For example, we can open the &quot;accepted synonym&quot; _Haliotis mariae_ and add this relationship.

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

### Under Related Taxa, we choose &quot;accepted synonym of&quot; and enter the related taxon _Haliotis mariae dentata.  _Our Authority is WoRMS and, if we want, we can enter a URL, a WoRMS AphiaID, an LSID identifier or any other appropriate authority.

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

### When we return to the taxon page, we see that the taxon relationship has been added to _Haliotis mariae.&quot;_

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

### If we look at _Haliotis mariae dentata_ we see that the relationship has been added to that record as well.

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

### Our updated taxon page now reflects the modifications made to the taxon relationship and the non-classification data.  If we created the relationship from _Haliotis mariae dentata_ the Related Taxa data would show that it is the &quot;junior synonym&quot; of _Haliotis mariae._

###

![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Editing Taxon classifications

In the above example, the taxon classification needed no changes.  We can edit a taxonomic classification several ways.  In this example, _Erronea subviridis dorsalis_, we need to correct the classification and add non-classification data such as the taxon status and author.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

When we click [Edit Classification] we find many red boxes that need attention.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

First, we must add the &quot;nomenclatural code&quot; ICZN.  We add a row to add the author text Schilder &amp; Schilder, 1938.  We add a row for the taxon status &quot;valid&quot; and a row for the source authority.  The &quot;display name&quot; and the &quot;scientific name&quot; will be autocreated.

In the classification, we need to correct &quot;animalia&quot; to &quot;Animalia&quot;

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

We&#39;ll need to delete the incorrect rows.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

We also want to add the subclass Caenogastropoda by adding a row, selecting &quot;subclass&quot; and entering Caenogastropoda.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Then we drag it to its correct position in the classification and Save Edits.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

When we return to our Taxon Page, the changes are complete.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Alternatively, we can edit a record by selecting a webservice source, deleting the erroneous classification and creating a new classification.  In this case, we would clone the WoRMS classification by clicking &quot;Clone Classification.&quot;

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Just as when creating a new taxon, we would complete the non-classification data and save the record.

##

![](data:image/*;base64,)

## **If you did not delete the erroneous**  **classification**  **before cloning a new one, it is very important that you return to the Taxon Page and delete it.**  Otherwise, there will two classifications and you will not be able to search for specimens or manage the taxonomy in the Hierarchical Classification Editor.

##

![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Note that deleting a classification for a taxon is different from deleting the taxon name, which is described below.

##
## Deleting a taxon

Users with taxonomic authority can delete taxon names that are without any validity or value to the Arctos users and to researchers.  Some &quot;invalid&quot; taxa are retained for legacy identifications.  But taxa that do not pass the Google test and are obviously without value may be deleted.

To perform &quot;The Google Test,&quot; search for the name (it&#39;s best in double quotes). If there are no results or results only referencing Arctos are found, it is probably safe to delete the name. Results which include only sources that draw from Arctos (such as GBIF) should be carefully scrutinized to determine if the results are in fact a circular reflection of Arctos data.

Here are several taxa that fail the Google test.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

_Do not_ delete names that are not &quot;current&quot; or &quot;accepted,&quot; or those that you do not agree with or won&#39;t use for some particular use case.  Do mark these names &quot;invalid&quot; in the &quot;taxon status&quot; field and link them to the accepted taxon.

To delete a record, search for the taxon.  Refresh GlobalNames to see if any of our webservices recognize the taxon.  In this case, we have refreshed _Cyprea ocellata_ and no webservice has come up.   It appears to be a misspelling of _Cypraea ocellata,_ which is an invalid but historically valuable term for _Naria ocellata.  _

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Also run the Google test.  In this case, one shell dealer has misspelled Cypraea, but the next two entries are for this Arctos entry.  There are several other errors that are from OCR translations of older texts in which Cypraea was misread as Cyprea.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

You must remove all links to other taxa and there must be no specimens using the species. This taxon meets all those requirements.  Click on [Edit Non-Classification Data] to bring up the Taxon Relationship screen.

  ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Follow the instructions in the red box to ensure that there is no one using the taxon and it should not be in the Arctos taxa tables.  Then click &quot;Delete taxon.&quot;

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Arctos will confirm the deletion.  You cannot reverse this but you can recreate the entire entry if needed.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)
